\begin_layout Subsection
Trust Islands for Effective Mutual Authentication
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The author's vision for mutual authentication for high-value services (e.g.,
 shopping, banking) is to use small federations of like services to mutually
 authenticate all of their many users to the member services.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, suppose there were a federation of banks in a single country
 (or currency zone), allowing only members that are chartered as banks with
 the relevant bank chartering authorities.
 Each user would be able to register with the bank federation that is relevant
 to them, and either obtain an ID within that federation, or to register
 an external ID for use in authenticating to banks in this federation.
 (Users could have more than one identify, of course.) Because such a federation
 would so exclusive for service membership it would be much more difficult
 for phishers to target its members -- in order to target them the phisher
 would have to either become a member of the highly exclusive federation
 (which can be made much more difficult than merely joining the TLS server
 PKI) or subvert the user-agent UIs.
 Anti-phishing improvements to the user-agent UIs would still be needed,
 but one half of the problem is instantly addressed by using exclusive federatio
ns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This works for shopping as well.
 Thing of Amazon and Yahoo! Shopping as such shopping federations where
 the entity running the federation allows relatively few member services
 (orders of magnitude fewer than on the global Internet, in the TLS server
 PKI).
 In effect we already have this, but we have no strong way to bind this
 into the user authentication experience.
 If these federations provided a user authentication mechanism that provides
 mutual authentication and channel binding to TLS then the weaknesses of
 the TLS server PKI would become completely irrelevant to the federations,
 their members, and their users.
\end_layout

